Diseases of Globalization
Globalization is being tested as severely as never before.
Everywhere, its tensions rumble.
The majority of Black Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia stagnate or struggle within economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war threatens now in Iraq.
For supporters of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Some regions of the world have gained great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions, however, have gained only meager benefits, particularly Black Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they struggle with.
The slow growth of Africa, claim American leaders, is caused by the incompetence of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced declining living standards over the past two decades while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the last in international comparisons on government quality (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow faster than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are exceptions).
Coastal countries tend to be more successful than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries bordering rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more successful than countries located far from the main markets.
Ces différences revêtent une grande importance.
Si les pays riches ne se soucient guère de ces problèmes structurels, les fossés entre les gagnants et les perdants continueront à s'élargir.
Si les pays riches rejettent la responsabilité sur les pays malchanceux en prétendant qu'ils sont d'une manière ou d'une autre culturellement ou politiquement inaptes à bénéficier de la mondialisation, nous créerons non seulement des poches plus profondes de pauvreté mais nous intensifierons également les troubles.
Ceci, à son tour, entraînera des niveaux accrus de violence, des réactions hostiles et le terrorisme.
Il est donc temps de passer à une approche plus sérieuse de la mondialisation que ne l'offrent les pays riches, et tout particulièrement l'Amérique.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the basic needs of the poorest peoples in the world.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds on their own to solve such problems.
Instead of seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation strikingly.
Control of diseases requires a health system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This sum is just a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functional health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases as long as it does not receive adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of blaming the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that are delaying their growth and economic development.
In some regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Wealthy countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In Black Africa, the main challenges relate to disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, more foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems relate to a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all consensus of Washington is outdated.
On the eve of the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
